\title{The origin of thermospin spectral dependence}

\author{I. Diniz, A. T. Costa}
\email{antc@if.uff.br}
\affiliation{Instituto de F\'isica, Universidade Federal Fluminense, 24210-346 Niter\'oi, RJ, Brazil}



\date{\today}

\begin{abstract}
Recent experimental evidence points to low-energy magnons as the primary contributors to the spin Seebeck effect.
This spectral dependence is puzzling since it is not observed on other thermocurrents in the same material. Here, we argue that the physical origin of this behavior is the scattering of magnons by processes which conserve the number of magnons. To evaluate this scattering, we derive the effective magnon-phonon interaction in a microscopic model: to the single-band Hubbard Hamiltonian we add the electron-phonon interaction. We find that the coupling with phonons induce a scattering which is very small for low-energy (or \textit{subthermal}) magnons but increases sharply above a certain energy  -- rendering magnons above this energy poor spin-current transporters. 



\end{abstract}






